column2: 1. Successfully understand what challenge code / data is
column4: 3. Successfully understand how to interact with code to gather useful output
column10: Dumping hex values of potential binary to examine file signatures
column13: Examine encoding (for example, base64 containing binary data)
column14: Ability to run a binary and get meaningful output
column15: Determine language from source code (C, assembly, etc.)
column16: The available code or data is not executable on your system
column17: Find functions or statements that use libraries designed to gather input from stdin or stdout (from user)
column20: Understand meaning of response to requests
column22: Input random values to successfully identify the structure and format of outputs
column23: Debugger enables stepping through program to see how interactions are occurring
column25: Successful identification of patterns (ex, mention of heap")"
column26: Available tools based on challenge help identify vulnerability (frequency analysis for crypto, forensics)
column27: Fuzzers blast input on binary and surface exploit for you by crashing program
column28: Craft a script that effectively interacts with program
column29: Able to program/script with Python and use pwntools, cryptographic libraries (pycryptodome), etc.
column31: If web CTF, successfully craft MITM using burpsuite to send malicious data for privilege escalation / impersonate someone else with cookie / etc.
column32: (Surprise) Tools are wrong, file results are misleading
column34: Discover that code mimics a certain challenge or vulnerability to throw off attackers
column35: Executable is made for a different OS
column37: Know how to effectively virtualize or emulate
column43: Identify reversible operations in the source code
column45: Identify stack protections: non-executable stack, randomized addresses, stack canaries
column46: (Time waster) Discover misleading belief that something is vulnerable
column48: Past experience informs what to look for
column51: Pattern isn't what you think it is
column53: Make assumptions to see whether/if something works
